<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-14T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-14T04:00:00-05:00" n="517" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d517">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/23495:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Standley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-14T12:00:00+03:00">August 14,
                                    1942—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received August 14—9:39 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>296. Mr. Harriman is reporting his conversations here direct to the
                            President through Navy codes and is keeping me fully informed.<note n="22" xml:id="d517fn22">No telegrams of significance from Harriman
                                relating to the Moscow conversations with Stalin, in addition to
                                those here printed, have been found in Department files or at the
                                Franklin D. Roosevelt Library, Hyde Park, N. Y.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>